There are many methods that we can use against strings:

1) indexOf():
str.indexOf("short")

2) slice():
str.slice(0, 5)

3)toUpperCase() or toLowerCase()
str.toUpperCase()


ES6 introduced 4 new string methods:

startsWith() //Return boolean
endsWith()//Return boolean      
includes()
repeat()

code.startsWith("DEF",3)//it will begin checking after 3 characters
code.endsWith("EF", 6)//6 means that we consider only the first 6 values ABCDEF, and yes this string ends with EF therefore we get *true*

hello.repeat(10) //Number of times sto repeat string.


String trim function:
---------------------
String.prototype.trimStart() / .trimEnd() #
String.prototype.trimStart() removes white space from the beginning of a string while String.prototype.trimEnd() removes them from the end.

We can also use .trimLeft() as an alias of .trimStart() and .trimRight() as an alias of .trimEnd().s

